  "local_port": 37300,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do i (a Java developer) get an Adobe Experience Manager (AEM) instance for learning the CMS? I'm not Adobe Parner.",
  "response": "As a Java developer looking to learn Adobe Experience Manager (AEM) without being an Adobe Partner, you have several options to get started:\n\n1. **AEM Trial**: Adobe often provides a trial version of AEM. Check the official Adobe website for any trial offerings. You'll typically need an Adobe ID to sign up for a trial, and you may need to fill out a form to request access.\n\n2. **AEM as a Cloud Service Demo**: Adobe offers demonstrations of AEM as a Cloud Service, which is a fully managed service that allows you to explore many of the features of AEM without needing to set up your own instance. Look for webinars or demo sessions hosted by Adobe.\n\n3. **AEM Community and User Groups**: Join the AEM community forums, groups, or social media channels. Participating in these communities can provide you with insights into accessing AEM, learning resources, and sometimes trial environments set up by other developers for educational purposes.\n\n4. **Online Tutorials and Resources**: There are numerous online resources, tutorials, and courses that can provide hands-on experience using AEM. Sites like LinkedIn Learning, Udemy, or Pluralsight might have courses that offer sandbox environments or simulated experiences.\n\n5. **Open Source Alternatives**: If you can't access AEM directly, consider using open source CMS platforms, such as Apache Jackrabbit or Magnolia CMS, which have some similarities to AEM in terms of functionality and concepts. This can help you understand content management best practices, though they will not be identical to AEM.\n\n6. **Documentation and Books**: Adobe provides extensive documentation for AEM. Leverage these resources to learn about the platform architecture, components, and best practices. Consider reading books or e-books about AEM that can guide you through various concepts and provide practical examples.\n\n7. **Local Development Environment**: If you gain access to an AEM instance (through trial, demo, or other means), you can set up a local development environment. AEM can be run locally in a way that allows for development and testing.\n\n8. **Contact Adobe Sales**: If you're serious about learning AEM, consider reaching out directly to Adobe's sales team or customer support. They may be able to guide you on how to get access to a trial or provide recommendations for learning.\n\nBy utilizing these resources, you can begin your journey into learning Adobe Experience Manager and how to develop on this platform.",
